      "title": "Viscosity",
      "conceptBody": "<h3>Viscosity</h3><p>&nbsp;Viscosity is internal friction in a fluid. Viscous forces opposes the motion of one portion of a fluid relative to the other.</p><p>The simplest example of viscous flow is motion of a fluid between two parallel plates.</p><p>The bottom plate is stationary and the top plate moves with constant velocity $\\text{\\vec{v}}$. The fluid in contact&nbsp;with each surface has same velocity at the surface. The flow speeds of intermediate layers of fluid increase uniformly from bottom to top, as shown by arrows. So the fluid layers slide smoothly over one another.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:277/171;\" src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"277\" height=\"171\"></figure><p>According to Newton, the frinctional force F (or viscous force) between two layers depends upon the following factors,</p><p>(i) Force $\\text{F}$ is directly proportional to the area (A) of the layers in contact, i.e.,</p><p>$\\text{F}\\propto \\text{A}$</p><p>(ii) For $\\text{F}$ is directly proportional to the velocity gradient $\\left( \\frac{\\text{dv}}{\\text{dy}} \\right)$ between the layers. Combining these two, we have</p><p>$\\begin{matrix} F\\propto A\\frac{dv}{dy} \\\\ F=\\eta A\\frac{dv}{dy} \\\\ \\end{matrix}$</p><p>Here, $\\eta $ is is constant of proportionality and is called coefficient of viscosity. Its value depends on the nature of fluid. The negative sign in the above equation shows that the direction of viscous force $\\text{F}$ is opposite to the direction of relative velocity of the layer.</p><p>The SI unit of $\\eta $ is $\\text{N}-\\text{s}/{{\\text{m}}^{2}}$. It is also called decapoise or Pascal second. Thus,</p><p>1 decapoise $=1\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ N}-\\text{s}/{{\\text{m}}^{2}}=1\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ Pa}-\\text{s}=10$ poise</p><p>Dimensions of $\\eta $ are $\\left[ \\text{M}{{\\text{L}}^{-1}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{T}}^{-1}} \\right]$</p><p>Coefficient of viscosity of water at ${{10}^{0}}\\text{C}$ is $\\eta =1.3\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{10}^{-3}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ N}$-s/m ${{\\text{m}}^{2}}$. Experiments show that coefficient of viscosity of a liquid decreases and its temperature rises.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db7cc03b9dcaf1afe205"
    },
    {
      "title": "Strokes Law",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Strokes Law</strong></h3><p>When an object moves through a fluid, it experiences a viscous force which acts in opposite direction of its velocity. The mathematics of the viscous force for an irregular object is difficult, we will consider here only the case of a small sphere moving through a fluid.</p><p>According to stokes law a spherical object of radius $\\text{r}$ moving at velocity $\\text{v}$ expression is viscous force given by</p><p>$\\text{F}=6\\pi \\eta \\text{rv }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\left( \\eta =\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ coefficient }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ of }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ viscosity }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ } \\right)$</p><p>This law is called <strong>Stoke's Law.&nbsp;</strong></p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db7cc03b9dcaf1afe206"
    },
    {
      "title": "Terminal Velocity",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Terminal Velocity $\\left( {{\\mathbf{V}}_{\\mathbf{T}}} \\right)$&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>Consider a small sphere falling from rest through a large column of viscous fluid. The forces acting on the sphere are,</p><p>(i) Weight $\\text{W}$ of the sphere acting vertically downwards</p><p>(ii) Upthrust ${{\\text{F}}_{\\text{t}}}$ acting vertically upwards</p><p>(iii) Viscous force ${{\\text{F}}_{\\text{v}}}$ acting vertically upwards, i.e., in a direction opposite to velocity of the sphere&nbsp;<br>Initially, ${{\\text{F}}_{\\text{v}}}=0$ $($ as $\\text{v}=0)$</p><p>$\\text{W}&gt;{{\\text{F}}_{\\text{t}}}$</p><p>and</p><p>and the sphere accelerates downwards. As the velocity of the sphere increases, ${{\\text{V}}_{\\text{v}}}$ increases. Eventually a stage in reached when</p><p>$\\text{W}={{\\text{F}}_{\\text{t}}}+{{\\text{F}}_{\\text{v}}}$ … (i)</p><p>After this net force on the sphere is zero and it moves downwards with a constant velocity called <strong>terminal velocity$\\left( {{\\mathbf{V}}_{\\mathbf{T}}} \\right)$.&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Substituting proper values in Eq. (i) we have</p><p>$\\frac{4}{3}\\pi {{\\text{r}}^{3}}\\rho \\text{g}=\\frac{4}{3}\\pi {{\\text{r}}^{3}}\\sigma \\text{g}+6\\pi \\eta r\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{V}}_{\\text{T}}}$</p><p>Here, $\\rho =$ density of sphere, $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\sigma =$ density of fluid</p><p>$\\eta =\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ coefficient }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ of }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ viscosity }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ of }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ fluid }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$</p><p>From Eq. (ii), we get ${{\\text{v}}_{\\text{T}}}=\\frac{2}{9}\\frac{{{\\text{r}}^{2}}\\left( \\rho -\\sigma \\right)\\text{g}}{\\eta }$</p><p>Figure shows the variation of the velocity $\\text{v}$ of the sphere with time</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"217\" height=\"190\"></p><p><strong>Tip : </strong>From the above expression we can see the terminal velocity of a spherical body is directly proportional to the difference in the densities of the body and the fluid $\\left( \\rho -\\sigma \\right)$, the terminal velocity is negative. This means that the body instead of falling, moves upward. This is why air bubbles rise up in water.</p>",
      "position": 2,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db7cc03b9dcaf1afe207"
    }
  ],
